El Paso Wasterwater Surveillance Time Series Analysis

April 19, 2022

  • Data processing
  • Time series analysis with the reported number of cases
  • Correlation analysis
  • Cross-correlation analysis between reported cases and WW concentration

Change of this version - this sessions briefly outline the changes you have made compared to earlier version. For example,

  1. Data cleaning and processing was changed

  2. Added the confidence intervals (using the conditional errors) in the output data

  3. Some unused code was kept at the later part of the script (after Under construction)

Analysis Objective: Process, analyze the time series data from WW Surveillance collected from El Paso, Texas 1. Process the data from multiple excel sheets to a combined dataset (long format)

  1. Exploratory analysis of time series figures with WW concentration

  2. Exploratory analysis of time series figures with COVID reported case data

  3. Cross-correlation between the case and WW concentration - see this link for reading https://online.stat.psu.edu/stat510/lesson/8/8.2

Data processing

Read in raw data and export an organized dataset. Time framework is between 6/22/2020 and 3/2/2022.

### Combine daily data into one dataset
#sheet names indicating data collection date
sheet_names <- excel_sheets("WW_data/WeeklyReports_ElPaso_Mezzari_2022.xlsx")
sheet_names
## read in and combine daily data first
dat <- lapply(sheet_names[-c(36,47,48)], function(x) { as.data.frame(read_excel("WW_data/WeeklyReports_ElPaso_Mezzari_2022.xlsx", sheet = x)) } )
comb.dat <-bind_rows(dat)[,-c(14,15)] %>% filter(`WWTP Site` %in% c("Fred Hurvey","Haskell","John T. Hickerson","Roberto Bustamante")) %>%
  rename(`Copies per L waste water (N1)`=`Copies/ L of wastewater (N1)`,
         `Copies per L waste water (N2)`=`Copies/ L of wastewater (N2)`)
## read in cumulative data sheet
# sheet 47: Cumulative Maresso from 2020 and 2021
FH.dat <- read_excel("WW_data/WeeklyReports_ElPaso_Mezzari_2022.xlsx", sheet=47, range="A6:I19") %>% mutate(`WWTP Site`="Fred Hurvey", `AVG Flowrate (MGD)`=6.05,`Date Collected`=as.Date(substr(`Sample Name`,4,11), format="%m/%d/%y"))
HS.dat <- read_excel("WW_data/WeeklyReports_ElPaso_Mezzari_2022.xlsx", sheet=47, range="K6:S19") %>% mutate(`WWTP Site`="Haskell", `AVG Flowrate (MGD)`=13.16,`Date Collected`=as.Date(substr(`Sample Name`,4,11), format="%m/%d/%y"))
JT.dat <- read_excel("WW_data/WeeklyReports_ElPaso_Mezzari_2022.xlsx", sheet=47, range="U6:AC18") %>% mutate(`WWTP Site`="John T. Hickerson",`AVG Flowrate (MGD)`=7.89,`Date Collected`=as.Date(substr(`Sample Name`,4,11), format="%m/%d/%y"))
RB.dat <- read_excel("WW_data/WeeklyReports_ElPaso_Mezzari_2022.xlsx", sheet=47, range="K6:S19") %>% mutate(`WWTP Site`="Roberto Bustamante",`AVG Flowrate (MGD)`=28.75,`Date Collected`=as.Date(substr(`Sample Name`,4,11), format="%m/%d/%y"))

# sheet 48: Cumulative CMMR from 2020 (6/22/2020 - 11/4/2020) - different format
# need to reformat the data
cmmr <- read_excel("WW_data/WeeklyReports_ElPaso_Mezzari_2022.xlsx", sheet=48,range="A2:G99") %>%
  mutate(`WWTP Site`=ifelse(`Sample Point WWTP RAW`=="FH", "Fred Hurvey", 
                            ifelse(`Sample Point WWTP RAW`=="HS", "Haskell", 
                                   ifelse(`Sample Point WWTP RAW`=="JT", "John T. Hickerson", "Roberto Bustamante"))),
         `Sample ID`=paste(`Sample Point WWTP RAW`, substr(`EP ID`, 2, 9), sep=" "),
         `Sample Name`=paste0(Concat, "/20"),
         `N1 C`=`AVG N1`, `N2 CT`=`AVG N2`)

# combine all data together
dat.processed <- bind_rows(comb.dat, FH.dat, HS.dat, JT.dat, RB.dat, cmmr[,c(2,4,8:12)])
# save the processed data 
writexl::write_xlsx(dat.processed, "WeeklyReports_ElPaso_Mezzari_2022_Processed.xlsx")  
# read in processed WWTP data
organized.data <- read_excel("WeeklyReports_ElPaso_Mezzari_2022_Processed.xlsx") %>% mutate(Date=as.Date(`Date Collected`))
sample_n(organized.data, 10) %>% knitr::kable()

Explorary analysis with the the WW concentration

#subset the data by WWTP
#sub<- organized.data[ which(organized.data$`WWTP Site`=='Fred Hurvey') ,]
FH<-subset(organized.data , `WWTP Site`=="Fred Hurvey", select = c("Date", "N1 C", "N2 CT")) %>% na.omit()
Has<-subset(organized.data , `WWTP Site`=="Haskell", select = c("Date", "N1 C", "N2 CT")) %>% na.omit()
Jth<-subset(organized.data , `WWTP Site`=="John T. Hickerson", select = c("Date", "N1 C", "N2 CT")) %>% na.omit()
Rb<-subset(organized.data , `WWTP Site`=="Roberto Bustamante", select = c("Date", "N1 C", "N2 CT")) %>% na.omit()

# Fred Hurvey
p.F <- ggplot(FH, aes(x=Date))+
            geom_line(aes(y = `N1 C`, colour = "N1")) +
              geom_line(aes(y=`N2 CT`,colour="N2"))+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(n = 10),limits = c(28,44))
### here instead of print every week, 
a <-p.F+labs(title="Fred Hurvey",x ="", y = "amplification cycles",colour=NULL)+
  scale_x_date(breaks = break.vec, date_breaks="4 weeks", date_labels = "%y-%m-%d")+ 
  theme(legend.position=c(0.85,0.9),legend.text = element_text(size=7),
        axis.text.x =element_text (angle=45,hjust=1))

# Haskell

b<-p.H+labs(title="Haskell",x ="", y = "amplification cycles",colour=NULL)+

break.vec <- c(seq(from = as.Date("2021-03-22"), to = as.Date("2022-1-27"),by = "week"))

## Fred Hurvey
FH_dt <- left_join(FH, subset(myData.df, myData.df$WWTP=="Hervey"), by="Date") %>% filter(Date >= as.Date("2021-03-24"))
coeff <- 4
overlay.F <- ggplot(FH_dt, aes(x=Date))+
  geom_line(aes(y = `N1 C`, colour = "N1")) +
  geom_line(aes(y=`N2 CT`,colour="N2"))+
  geom_line(aes(y = CaseRate/coeff, x=Date, color = "Cases per 100k"))+
  labs(title="Fred Hurvey",x ="Collection Date", y = "Amplification cycles",colour=NULL)+
  scale_y_continuous(   # Custom the Y scales:
    name = "Amplification cycles", # Features of the first axis
    sec.axis = sec_axis(trans=~.*coeff, name="Number of cases per 100k population"))+ # Add a second axis and specify its features
  scale_x_date(breaks = break.vec, date_breaks="week", date_labels = "%y-%m-%d")+ 
  theme(legend.position=c(0.1,0.9),legend.text = element_text(size=7),
        axis.text.x =element_text (angle=90,hjust=1))+
  theme(axis.line.y.right = element_line(color = "red"))
overlay.F

Correlation analysis

Briefly describe the analysis - for example, let \(y_{1t}\) and \(y_{t}\) describe the two time series variables for \(y_1\) and \(y_2\), blah blah blah.

Correlation analysis of Hasketll and N1

#correlation analysis:Haskell and N1 CT
stackoverflow_HN1 <- HS_dt %>%
  dplyr::select(Date,`N1 C`, CaseRate)
stackoverflow_HN1<-stackoverflow_HN1[complete.cases(stackoverflow_HN1),]#cleaning data: delete NA

stackOverflowts <- ts(data = stackoverflow_HN1[, c("CaseRate","N1 C")], # selecting 2 variables
                       start = c(2021, 04), # start date
                       end = c(2022, 1), # end date 
                       frequency = 52)

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
# acf Haskell time series
stackOverflowts[, c("CaseRate")] %>% 
  acf(lag.max = 300, 
      main = "Autocorrelation Plot - Haskell")

# pacf Haskell time series
stackOverflowts[, c("CaseRate")] %>%
  pacf(lag.max = 300,
       main = "Partial Autocorrelation Plot - Haskell")


# acf N1 C time series
stackOverflowts[, c("N1 C")] %>% 
  acf(lag.max = 300, 
      main = "Autocorrelation Plot - N1 C")

# pacf N1 C time series
stackOverflowts[, c("N1 C")] %>%
  pacf(lag.max = 300,
       main = " N1 C")

#correlation analysis: Bustamante and N1 CT

Cross-correlation analysis between reported cases and WW concentration

Kehe - I think cross-correlation may help us identify the leading time when virus in WW started to show a pikes before the cases were increasing.

N1_ts <- ts(FH_dt$`N1 C`, frequency=365, start=c(year(minday1), as.numeric(format(minday1, "%j"))))
case_ts <- ts(case_all$ncase_7d_avg, frequency=365, start=c(year(minday2), as.numeric(format(minday2, "%j"))))

## intersection (only overlapping times)
dat_int <- ts.intersect(test_ts, case_ts)
